    elif sort_by == 'updated_at_desc':
        search = search.sort('-updated_at')

    return search
```

2. Make sure that `updated_at` is properly mapped in your Elasticsearch index. It should typically be mapped as a `date` type field.

3. If you're using a template, you'll need to add the sort options to your HTML. For example:

```html
<select name="sort">
    <option value="">Sort by...</option>
    <option value="updated_at_asc" {% if request.GET.sort == 'updated_at_asc' %}selected{% endif %}>
        Updated (Oldest first)
    </option>
    <option value="updated_at_desc" {% if request.GET.sort == 'updated_at_desc' %}selected{% endif %}>
        Updated (Newest first)
    </option>
</select>
```

4. If you want to maintain the sort parameter across pagination or other filters, make sure to include it in any query string building logic you might have.

The key points to remember:
- Elasticsearch sorting uses `-` prefix for descending order
- Make sure the field is properly indexed in Elasticsearch
- The field name in the sort should match the field name in your Elasticsearch mapping

